Is java realy use in algo firm?

Yes, Java is genuinely used in many algorithmic trading firms, especially for backend trading infrastructure.

Examples include:

* JPMorgan Chase
* Goldman Sachs
* Morgan Stanley
* Citadel
* Two Sigma

However, the role of Java varies:

| Component                       | Common Language |
| ------------------------------- | --------------- |
| Trading backend services        | Java            |
| Risk systems                    | Java            |
| Order Management Systems        | Java            |
| Market data processing          | Java/C++        |
| Ultra-low-latency HFT execution | C++             |
| Research and data science       | Python          |

A typical trading stack might look like:

```text
Python      -> Research & strategy development
Java        -> Backend trading platform
C++         -> Lowest-latency execution components
Linux       -> Production servers
```

If your goal is a backend/server-side career and you do not want embedded development, Java is one of the strongest choices. 
Many trading firms hire Java engineers for distributed systems, market data platforms, risk engines, and order management systems running on Linux servers. 
Not every trading job is ultra-low-latency C++; there are many Java-based roles as well.
